First Data Analysis Project¶

The objective of this project is to determine the top locations in the southeast region of Brazil to extract solar and wind energy. In addition, it would be beneficial to forecast future solar and wind conditions to estimate potential energy production.

1.0 Obtain Data¶

  • Data has been collected from the following website:
    https://www.kaggle.com/PROPPG-PPG/hourly-weather-surface-brazil-southeast-region
  • As a reference, the following table includes the list of columns with their description:
Label Description
wsid Weather station id
wsnm Name station (usually city location or nickname)
elvt Elevation
lat Latitude
lon Longitude
inme Station number (INMET number) for the location
city City
prov State (Province)
mdct Observation Datetime (complete date: date + time)
date Date of observation
yr The year (2000-2016)
mo The month (0-12)
da The day (0-31)
hr The hour (0-23)
prcp Amount of precipitation in millimetres (last hour)
stp Air pressure for the hour in hPa to tenths (instant)
smax Maximum air pressure for the last hour in hPa to tenths
smin Minimum air pressure for the last hour in hPa to tenths
gbrd Solar radiation KJ/m2
temp Air temperature (instant) in celsius degrees
dewp Dew point temperature (instant) in celsius degrees
tmax Maximum temperature for the last hour in celsius degrees
dmax Maximum dew point temperature for the last hour in celsius degrees
tmin Minimum temperature for the last hour in celsius degrees
dmin Minimum dew point temperature for the last hour in celsius degrees
hmdy Relative humid in % (instant)
hmax Maximum relative humid temperature for the last hour in %
hmin Minimum relative humid temperature for the last hour in %
wdsp Wind speed in metres per second
wdct Wind direction in radius degrees (0-360)
gust Wind gust in metres per second

2.2 Remove Unwanted Columns¶

Don't need the stations name 'wsnm' or station number 'inme' just use stations id 'wsid'. For now we don't need location of the station so remove 'elvt', 'lat', 'lon','city', 'prov'. Can get the date and time from 'mdct' so remove the following column 'date' 'yr', 'mo', 'da', 'hr'.

Use .drop() to remove columns.

Takes too long to run .drop() so commented it out.
Alternatively you could create a list of columns that you would want to read in from the start.

In [4]:
# df.drop(['wsnm', 'inme', 'elvt', 'lat', 'lon', 'city', 'prov', 'date', 'yr', 'mo', 'da', 'hr'], axis=1)


2.3 Change Index¶

Change the index from integer to Observation Datetime (mdct) .set_index() and change the data type from object to datetime .to_datetime() since we will be performing time series analysis.

In [5]:
df = df.set_index('mdct')
df.index = pd.to_datetime(df.index)

Create a list when 'prcp' to 'gust' columns are equal to zero and assume the weather station was offline since all values are equal to zero.

  • Out[13] Shows total number of zeros for each column.
  • Out[14] Shows total number of zeros after dropping indexes when the weather station was assumed offline.

As you can see the number of zeros has dropped significantly. However, there are still a lot of zeros in the Solar Radiation column so let's explore that next.

2.7 Correct Solar Radiation Data¶

Plot solar radiation VS time to see where the sources of zeros are coming from.

  • Out[15] Found a large source of zeros at the start of the data series so maybe the weather station were not collecting solar radiation value.
  • Out[16] Zoomed in at a two week time period we can see that data is not being collected at certain time which makes sense because there is very little solar energy at night.

Turn the Null data to zero to in order to perform forecasting later on In[17].

  • Out[18] See that Null have turned to zero.

2.8 Correct Wind Data¶

Let's check if there is any missing data in the wind speed collection.

  • Out[19] There are 4850 missing so these should be removed to perform forecasts later on.
  • In[20] Interpolate wind speed data when Null.
  • Out[21] After interpolating there are no longer any missing values.

In [19]:
#Count number of missing values.
data_ws_online.wdsp.isna().sum()
Out[19]:
4850
In [20]:
#Interpolate missing values.
data_ws_online_wind=data_ws_online.copy()
data_ws_online_wind['wdsp'].interpolate('linear', limit_direction='both', inplace=True)
In [21]:
#Count number of missing values after interpolation.
data_ws_online_wind.wdsp.isna().sum()
Out[21]:
0


2.9 Clean Up The Data Set¶

From sections 2.6 to 2.8, we can apply these steps to clean up all the weather stations. This is quick fix however going through each weather station individually is necessary to obtain accurate results.


First step is to check when the weather stations are online and create a new dataframe In[22].

Second step is to set solar radiation from Null to zero as per section 2.7 In[24].

  • Out[25] As you can see there are no longer any missing values for solar radiation.

The last step is to interpolate the wind speed as per section 2.8 In[24].

  • Out[26] Demonstrates that wind speed has been corrected. The blue segments shows when the wind speed was equal to zero.

df_online = df[((df['prcp']!=0) & (df['stp']!=0) & (df['smax']!=0) & (df['smin']!=0) & (df['temp']!=0) &

Find three weather stations for both highest solar radiation and highest wind speed.

Solar Radiation - Stations 178, 334, 356
Wind Speed - Stations 370, 379, 375

# Find the mean solar radiation and wind speed for each weather station and then rank them.
df_wsid_mean=df_wsid.mean()

df_wsid_mean['Wind_Speed_Ranking'] = df_wsid_mean['wdsp'].rank(ascending=False)

We can see that in the winter months (Southern Hemisphere) solar radiation drops which makes sense since the amount a day time decreases in the winter.

Experimenting with Forecasting¶

Since there is a seasonal trend we are going to use Holt-Winters forecasting technique. Created a User Defined Function to forecast solar radiation and wind speed for a specified weather stations.

In [36]:
def SolarRadiationForecast(dataframe):
    
    # Test date runs for one year
    start_train_date = dataframe.index[0]
    end_train_date =dataframe.index[-8735]
    start_test_date=dataframe.index[-8736]
    end_test_date = dataframe.index[-1]

    train =dataframe[start_train_date : end_train_date]
    test =dataframe[start_test_date : end_test_date]
    
    data_forecast_gbrd1=dataframe.resample('D').mean()
    data_forecast_gbrd1['gbrd'].fillna(data_forecast_gbrd1['gbrd'].mean(), inplace=True)
    train=train.resample('D').mean()
    train['gbrd'].fillna(train['gbrd'].mean(), inplace=True)
    test=test.resample('D').mean()
    test['gbrd'].fillna(test['gbrd'].mean(), inplace=True)
    
    # Plot1 Training and test data
    ax=train.gbrd.plot(figsize=(15,8),color='blue')
    ax.set_ylabel('Solar Radiation (KJ/m2)')
    test.gbrd.plot(figsize=(15,8),color='green', ax=ax)
    ax.set_xlabel('Date')
    ax.legend(['Training Data','Test Data'])
    plt.title('Weather Station 334')
    
     # Plot2 Seasonal Data
    sm.tsa.seasonal_decompose(train.gbrd).plot()
    result = sm.tsa.stattools.adfuller(train.gbrd)
    plt.show(  )
    
    # Plot3 Forecast
    holt_avg=test.copy()
    fit1=ExponentialSmoothing(np.asarray(train['gbrd']), seasonal_periods =365, trend= 'add',seasonal= 'add').fit()
    holt_avg['Holt_Winter'] = fit1.forecast(len(test))
    plt.figure(figsize=(15,15))
    ax=plt.plot(train['gbrd'], label = 'Train Data',color='blue')
    plt.plot(test['gbrd'], label = 'Test Data',color='green')
    plt.plot(holt_avg['Holt_Winter'], label = 'Holt Winter Model',color='red')
    plt.legend()
    plt.ylabel('Solar Radiation (KJ/m2)')
    plt.xlabel('Date')
    plt.title('Weather Station 334')
    rms = sqrt(mean_squared_error(test.gbrd, holt_avg.Holt_Winter))
    print('RMS: ' ,rms)
    
    return

def WindSpeedForecast(dataframe):
    
    # Test date runs for one year
    start_train_date = dataframe.index[0]
    end_train_date =dataframe.index[-8759]
    start_test_date=dataframe.index[-8760]
    end_test_date = dataframe.index[-1]

    train =dataframe[start_train_date : end_train_date]
    test =dataframe[start_test_date : end_test_date]
    
    data_forecast_wdsp=dataframe.resample('D').mean()
    data_forecast_wdsp['wdsp'].fillna(data_forecast_wdsp['wdsp'].mean(), inplace=True)
    train=train.resample('D').mean()
    train['wdsp'].fillna(train['wdsp'].mean(), inplace=True)
    test=test.resample('D').mean()
    test['wdsp'].fillna(test['wdsp'].mean(), inplace=True)
    
    #Plot1 Training and test data
    ax= train.wdsp.plot(figsize=(15,8),color='blue')
    ax.set_ylabel('Wind Speed (m/s)')
    test.wdsp.plot(figsize=(15,8),ax=ax,color='green')
    ax.set_xlabel('Date')
    ax.legend(['Training Data','Test Data'])
    plt.title('Weather Station 334')
    
    #Plot2 Seasonal Data
    sm.tsa.seasonal_decompose(train.wdsp).plot()
    result = sm.tsa.stattools.adfuller(train.wdsp)
    plt.show()
    
    #Plot3 Forecast
    holt_avg=test.copy()
    fit1=ExponentialSmoothing(np.asarray(train['wdsp']), seasonal_periods =365, trend= 'add',seasonal= 'add').fit()
    holt_avg['Holt_Winter'] = fit1.forecast(len(test))
    plt.figure(figsize=(15,15))
    plt.plot(train['wdsp'], label = 'Train Data',color='blue')
    plt.plot(test['wdsp'], label = 'Test Data',color='green')
    plt.plot(holt_avg['Holt_Winter'], label = 'Holt_Winter',color='red')
    plt.legend()
    plt.ylabel('Wind Speed (m/s)')
    plt.xlabel('Date')
    plt.title('Weather Station 334')
    rms = sqrt(mean_squared_error(test.wdsp, holt_avg.Holt_Winter))
    print('RMS: ' ,rms)
   
    return
